## attack  (the offensive read)
- `vectors`: the attack surfaces / structural weaknesses, stated offensively (plain text — do NOT
  prefix the 💥 emoji; the renderer adds it).
- `beat_baseline`: one concrete way to beat this baseline.
- `exploit_flaw`: one concrete way to exploit the central flaw.

## claims  (1-5, the ARA-disciplined epistemic floor)
- `title`: a short mechanism-level title. Apply the name-deletion test — strike the paper's own
  system/model names; if nothing transferable survives, you wrote attribution, not a claim.
- `statement`: the mechanism/relationship — the reusable WHY. NO run numbers, scores, or step
  counts (those live in `sources`); the subject is a mechanism, never a named recipe.
- `falsification`: a concrete observation that would disprove the claim — about the system/world,
  not a re-run of the same gate.
- `status`: hypothesis / supported / refuted, with an optional `status_note` caveat.
- `sources`: for every load-bearing value, a `{quote, location}` — the verbatim line copied from
  the paper and where it lives. Never invent a source; if you cannot quote it, drop the value.
  Quote-or-drop.
- `tags`, `flags`: keyword tags, and functional-defect `flags` (`no_ablation`, `math_decoration`,
  `result_ungrounded`, `method_orphaned`, `suspicious_dependency`) that trigger a downstream lens.

You do NOT propose vault edges (a separate citation-grounding step mints them), and you write NO
Insight / Thought / Decision content — those are the operator's to author, never auto-generated.

Output MUST be valid JSON matching the provided schema.
